{"id":"2212.06745","submitter":"Naresh Dadhich","authors":"Naresh Dadhich","title":"Could Buchdahl star be a Virial star ?","comments":"6 pages, Title changed, abstract modified. Overall arguemnts and\n  analysis revamped and sharpened. New references added","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Buchdahl star is the most compact object without horizon and it is defined by\nthe potential $\\Phi(R) = 4/9$ and black hole by $\\Phi(R) = 1/2$, where $\\Phi(R)\n= (MR-Q^2/2)/(R^2+a^2)$ for Kerr-Newman charged and rotating object. It turns\nout that in terms of gravitational and non-gravitational energy, the former is\ndefined when gravitational energy is half of non-gravitational energy while the\nlatter when the two are equal. If an infinitely dispersed system of bare mass\n$M$ collapses under its own gravity to radius $R$, total energy inside would be\n$E_{tot}(R)=M-E_{grav}(R)$. That is, energy inside is increased by the amount\nequivalent to gravitational energy which may manifest as internal or binding\nenergy. If the interior consists of free particles in motion interacting only\nthrough gravity (as is the case for Vlasov kinetic matter), then internal\n(gravitational) energy would be kinetic energy and the defining condition for\nBuchdahl star would be kinetic energy equal to half of non-gravitational\n(potential) energy. It could then be construed that equilibrium of Buchdahl\nstar interior is governed by the celebrated Virial theorem (kinetic energy\nequal to half of potential energy). Thus it could be thought of as a Virial\nstar.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 11 Dec 2022 12:20:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Dec 2022 07:04:48 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 4 Mar 2023 15:49:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-07"}
